 The sea is ours : Bolivia, stuck, hopes the court will reopen the way to the Pacific
Sailors patrol in an armored boat at the naval headquarters in La Paz.
Public buildings are flying a blue flag like the ocean.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases display the following motto:  The sea is our right.
It's a duty to get it back.
Across blockaded Bolivia, the memory of a coastline lost to Chile in a bloody 19th century resource conflict is still fresh, as is the desire to sail the Pacific Ocean once again.
These hopes have not been so palpable for several decades, as Bolivia awaits a decision from the International Court of Justice, which will be handed down on 1 October, after five years of deliberations.
 Bolivia has the will, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course expects a positive outcome , explains Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will be watching the International Court of Justice's decision on large screens across the country, hoping that the Hague court will rule in favor of Bolivia's claim.Bolivia wants Chile to be obliged to negotiate a sovereign passage to the ocean to Bolivia after decades of sporadic negotiations.
Evo Morales, Bolivia's charismatic indigenous president (who faces a controversial re-election battle next year), also has a lot to say about the decision that will be made on Monday.
 We are so close to being able to return to the Pacific Ocean , he said at the end of August.
But some analysts believe that there is little chance that the court will rule in favor of Chile and that little will change, even if it does.
The Netherlands-based UN body has no power to grant Chile territory, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice is giving its decision six months after the final arguments shows that the case  was not complicated , explains Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from helping the Bolivian cause, the last four years may have even been detrimental to it.
 The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration, said Zárate.
Morales' bellicose rhetoric has undermined any remaining Chilean goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to exchange, but after that it will be very difficult to organise talks.
The last exchange of ambassadors between the two countries took place in 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, who represents Bolivia at the Hague, rejected the idea that the Court's decision-making was unusually rapid.
Monday will bring Bolivia "an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile" and a chance to "end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits", he said.
Calzadilla also challenged the fact that Morales - who remains to this day one of the most popular presidents in Latin America - was using the maritime issue as a political crutch.
 Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean , he added.
 The Court's decision is an opportunity to see that we must get rid of the past. 
