John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence, a trend that continued in 2018 with further excellent examination results reinforced by collective and individual success in sports, the arts, music and other community activities.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best possible service to pupils and their parents.
Independent schools work to prepare their students for higher education, their chosen careers and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector able to design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we find that contemporary languages remain popular and desired subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, "If you talk to a man in a language he understands, you talk to his head".
If you speak to him in his own language, you speak to his heart.
It reminds us that we cannot rely on English to build relationships and build trust with people in other countries.
If we look at the excellent results in the examinations this year, we see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained the highest grade, A.
Data from the 74 SCIS member schools show that 72% of students achieved the highest grade, A, in Mandarin, as did 72% of students who studied German, 69% of students who studied French and 63% of students who studied Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as absolutely essential skills for children and young people in the future.
Now, languages as subjects are organised along with science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that 17% of the difficulties employers face in recruiting candidates are related to insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore becoming increasingly vital in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job opportunities requiring languages, these skills are essential in our globalised world.
Whatever career choice, a person who speaks a second language will have a real advantage in the future from this lasting skill.
Being able to communicate directly with foreigners automatically puts the multilingual person ahead of his competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4,000 adults in the UK, 75% of them did not have sufficient foreign language skills to hold a conversation, with French being the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage (15%).
This is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
By speaking several languages, including those of emerging economies, children will have a better chance of finding a rewarding job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Many of these will focus on contemporary classical languages, while others will teach languages considered important for the UK in the run-up to 2020, including Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever your child's preferences, several languages will be available in independent schools, with staff specialised in the field.
Independent schools in Scotland want to provide a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It is clear that in today's global business environment, languages remain of vital importance to the future of the country.
Modern languages should be considered as international communication skills.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scotland's young people.
It's got to be done.
John Edward is the head of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
