North Korea says that disarmament cannot be unilateral without trust.
On Saturday, North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations that the continuation of sanctions was reinforcing his mistrust of the United States and that it would be impossible for his country to unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons under these circumstances.
At the annual general assembly of the world body, Ri Yong Ho said that North Korea had taken important goodwill measures last year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site and committing itself not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
 However, we do not see any corresponding response from the US , he regretted.
In the absence of trust in the United States, we will fear for our national security and, in such circumstances, there is no way that we will be the first to disarm unilaterally.
While reiterating North Korea's well-known criticisms of Washington's opposition to a "step-by-step" approach to denuclearisation under which North Korea would be rewarded if it took incremental steps, his statement proved important in that it did not reject the idea of unilateral denuclearisation as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump, made on June 12 in Singapore at the first-ever summit between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader, when Kim pledged to work towards the "denuclearisation of the Korean Peninsula" while Trump promised to guarantee the security of North Korea.
North Korea is seeking to formally end the Korean War (1950-53), but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
The US is insisting that North Korea denuclearize first and is increasing the pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve their goal in a coercive manner, even opposing "the declaration of the end of the war".
Those who think that these sanctions can make us bend do not know us.
The problem is that the continuation of sanctions increases our mistrust. 
Ri made no comment about the second summit between Kim and Trump highlighted by the US leader at the UN earlier this week.
The minister instead highlighted three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, and added:  If the party concerned with the denuclearization issue was South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula would not be in such a deadlock. 
Still, Ri's tone was radically different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable that North Korean missiles would be pointed at North American soil after the evil President Trump called Kim a "suicide missile man".
Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea at the United Nations, did not hold back this year from praising Kim's courage in implementing disarmament measures, but added that much more needs to be done and that sanctions will not be lifted until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said that "no deadline has been set". "It can take two years, three years, or five months; it doesn't matter", he said.
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council last Thursday that:  The Security Council sanctions must be firmly and systematically maintained until complete, final and verified denuclearization. 
The Security Council has unanimously strengthened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to curb funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programmes.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then announced that he would travel to Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times this year, but his last trip was somewhat disastrous.
In July, he left Pyongyang claiming that progress had been made, but within hours, North Korea denounced his "gangster-like" methods.
In a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the United States took equivalent action.
He has said that Kim is demanding the security guarantees Trump promised Singapore, and efforts to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard: students taking a break from school
This year, Harvard University introduced a new class that allows all undergraduate students to get more sleep and fights the growing male-dominated trend of studying while drinking caffeine all night.
A professor has observed that most students at the world's best universities are not able to care for themselves
The course, designed by Charles Czeisler, a sleep medicine professor at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him.
And at the end, a student came up to me and said, "Why do I only get this in my senior year?"
She claimed that no one had ever talked to her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me, he told The Telegraph.
This course, which was taught for the first time this year, explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their academic and physical performance and their general well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university's chief medical officer, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The class hour consists of various interactive exercises.
One of the sections shows a picture of a dormitory containing various objects (coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, books, etc.) that students click on to learn about the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a bedtime routine.
In another section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression and cancer.
A campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
We know that this will not change the behaviour of the students instantly.
However, we believe they have a right to know this information - just as you have a right to know what the health effects of smoking are", added Professor Czeisler.
He says the culture of pride in "sleeping through the night" still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students are making sleep deprivation a growing problem.
Getting enough and good quality sleep should be the secret weapon of students to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid gaining weight, as lack of sleep puts the brain in a 'nutrition mode', making them hungry all the time.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old chemistry and physical biology student from California, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after he was one of his students last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said that the course had opened his eyes and made him insist that it be offered to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all postgraduate students a similar programme of study before joining the reputable institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students have an alarm for both bedtime and wake-up time, and be aware of the harmful effects of blue light from electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and lead to sleep disturbances.
