A new cancer vaccine allows the immune system to detect cancer cells
A new cancer vaccine allows the immune system to  detect  cancer cells and kill them
As part of the treatment, the vaccine tells the immune system how to recognize cancer cells
This technique involves extracting immune cells from a patient and modifying them in the laboratory
They can then detect a protein that is common to many cancers, and then they are reinjected
An experimental vaccine is showing encouraging results in patients with various types of cancer.
One woman who received the vaccine, which is designed to teach the immune system to recognize cancer cells, had her ovarian cancer disappear for more than 18 months.
The method involves taking immune cells from a patient and modifying them in the laboratory so that they can detect the HER2 protein, which is common in many cancers, and then injecting them again.
Professor Jay Berzofsky, of the US National Cancer Institute based in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our findings indicate that we have a very promising vaccine".
According to Professor Berzofsky, the HER2 protein  causes an increase in several types of cancer , including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancer.
A similar approach, which involves taking immune cells to train them to target cancer cells, has been proven to work in the treatment of a type of leukaemia.
