In order not to disappoint everyone when they finally learned the truth about his sexuality, he wanted to prove that he was "something", he continued.
The two-time Olympic bronze medalist is now a prominent LGBT activist and took advantage of his participation in this year's Commonwealth Games in Australia to call for more countries to decriminalise homosexuality.
He said he spoke out because he felt lucky to be able to live openly without ramifications and that he wanted to give hope back to others.
The three-time world champion said he "didn't expect" to fall in love with a man - American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013
Daley married the Oscar winner last year, 20 years her senior, but he said the age difference had never been an issue.
 Having seen so much at such a young age  - he participated in his first Olympic Games at the age of 14 and his father died of cancer three years later - he confidently says that it was difficult to find someone of his age who had experienced the same ups and downs.
In June, they became parents to a son named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley claimed that his entire outlook had changed.
"If you had asked me last year, I would have thought only of winning a gold medal", he said.
You know what, there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal, this is Robbie.
His son is named after his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 from brain cancer.
Daley said that his father had not accepted that he was going to die and that one of the last things he asked him was if they already had their tickets for London 2012, as he wanted to sit in the front row.
I couldn't tell him, 'Dad, you're not going to be there to be in the front row,' he said.
I was holding his hand when he stopped breathing and it took him to stop breathing and die for me to finally recognize that he was not invincible, he added.
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Summer Olympics and won a bronze medal.
 It was everything I had dreamed of my whole life - to dive in front of a home crowd at the Olympic Games, there is nothing better , he said.
In addition, it inspired his first song choice - Proud by Heather Small - which had accompanied him in the preparations for the Olympics and still gave him goosebumps.
