A Mickelson out of shape on the Ryder Cup bench Saturday.
American Phil Mickelson will set a record on Sunday in his 47th Ryder Cup match, but he'll have to straighten out to avoid an unfortunate step.
Mickelson, who was competing in the biannual event for the 12th time, a record, was disqualified by Saturday's fourball and foursome captain Jim Furyk.
Instead of being in the thick of the action, as he so often was for the United States, the five-time grand champion split his day between the role of endurance and fine-tuning his pitch play in an attempt to remedy his ailments.
He was never the greatest of all leaders, even at the peak of his career, and at 48 years of age, he is not the most suitable for the difficult Golf National, where the long rough systematically punishes stray shots.
And as if the course wasn't scary enough, Mickelson, in Sunday's ninth match, faces British Open winner Francesco Molinari, who teamed up this week with Tommy Fleetwood to win all four of their matches.
If the Americans, down four at the start of the 12 singles matches, get off to a good start, Mickelson's match could prove to be absolutely crucial.
Furyk expressed his confidence in his man, but he couldn't say much else.
"He fully understood the role he had to play today, gave me a pat on the back, put his arm around me and said he would be ready tomorrow", Furyk said.
He has great confidence in himself.
He's a legendary champion and he's added so much to these teams in the past, just like this week.
I probably didn't see him play two games.
I had planned more, but that's the way it happened and that's the way we felt we should proceed.
He wants to be there, like everyone else.
On Sunday, Mickelson will beat Nick Faldo's record for the most Ryder Cup matches played.
This could mark the end of a Ryder Cup career that never quite reached the heights of his individual record.
Mickelson has 18 wins, 20 losses and seven draws, although Furyk has claimed that his presence has brought some tangible elements to the team.
He is funny, sarcastic, witty, likes to make fun of people, and is a great guy to have in the team room", he explained.
I think the younger players had a lot of fun competing against him this week, which was fun to watch.
He's doing more than playing.
The captain of the European team Thomas Bjorn knows that the lead could soon disappear
Thomas Bjorn, the European captain, knows from experience that a small lead before the last day of the Ryder Cup can easily turn into a tough race.
The Dane played his first match in 1997 in Valderrama, where a team captained by Seve Ballesteros had a five-point lead over the Americans, but eventually climbed to the top of the standings with the smallest possible gap on the finish line, winning 141⁄2-131⁄2.
"You keep reminding yourself that we were going wide at Valderrama; we had a big lead at Brookline, where we failed, as well as at Valderrama, where we won, but just by a little bit", said Bjorn, after watching the 2018 Rankings win 5-3 on both Friday and yesterday at the National Golf to lead 10-6.
History will prove to me and all the members of this team that this is not the end.
You'll have to do it tomorrow.
Go and do whatever you have to do.
It's not over until we get the points on the board.
We have one goal, which is to try and win this trophy, and that's what we have to stay focused on.
I always said I focus on the 12 players on our side, but we are very aware of what is happening on the other side - they are the best players in the world.
Delighted with the performances of his players on a difficult golf course, Bjorn added:  I would never go that far.
Tomorrow is a whole different set of sleeves.
Tomorrow, it's the individual performances that will be presented and it's a whole different story.
It's great to be with a teammate when things are going well, but when you're out there on your own, you're being tested to the full extent of your ability as a golfer.
That's the message to the players, is to make the best of yourselves tomorrow.
When you leave your partner behind, he has to go get the best out of himself, too.
Unlike Bjorn, his counterpart Jim Furyk will seek to ensure that his players achieve better results individually than as teammates, with the exception of Jordan Spieth and Justin Thomas, who got three out of four points.
Furyk himself experienced both ends of these final day twists, having been part of the winning team in Brookline before losing at the end of the Miracle of Medina, where Europe took the victory.
"I remember every word", he said in response to a question about how Ben Crenshaw, the captain in 1999, had rallied his players on the last day.
We have 12 important meetings tomorrow, but you'd want to make this quick start as you saw in Brookline, as you saw in Medina.
This dynamic, when it goes in one direction, puts a lot of pressure on the midfield games.
We set up our training accordingly and put the guys like we thought we were supposed to do, we're trying to do magic tomorrow. 
Thomas was given the task of leading the counterattack and will face Rory McIlroy in the first-class duel, with Paul Casey, Justin Rose, Jon Rahm, Tommy Fleetwood and Ian Poulter, the other Europeans in the top half of the standings.
"I've accompanied this group of guys in this order because I think it covers the whole course", Bjorn said of his singles selections.
Germany's new warship delayed again
According to local media, the new German Navy frigate was supposed to be commissioned in 2014 to replace the aging warships dating back to the Cold War, but it will not be commissioned until at least next year due to faulty systems and exponential spending.
According to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quotes a military spokesman, the commissioning of the  Rheinland-Pfalz , the flagship of the new frigates of Baden-Württemberg, has been postponed to the first half of 2019.
The ship was scheduled to enter the Navy in 2014, but troubling post-delivery issues jeopardized the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Bade-Wurtemberg class ships that the Navy ordered in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen class frigates.
It is certain that they will be equipped with a powerful gun, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as certain stealth technologies, such as a radar, infrared and reduced acoustic signature.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods - it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates for up to two years outside home ports.
According to Die Zeit, however, the incessant delays mean that the forward-thinking warships - which should enable Germany to project its strength overseas - will already be obsolete when they are commissioned.
Last year, the cursed frigate F125 made headlines when the German Navy officially refused to commission the ship and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipbuilder after its delivery.
The reasons for this return were little known, but the German media mentioned a number of software and hardware defects that rendered the warship useless in case of deployment on a combat mission.
The software flaws were particularly significant as the Baden-Württemberg class ships will be operated by a crew of around 120 sailors, which is half the number of the old Bremen class frigates.
In addition, it appears that the ship is significantly overloaded, which reduces its efficiency and reduces the Navy's ability to make future improvements.
It is estimated that the 7,000-tonne Rheinland-Pfalz weighs twice as much as the similar class of ships used by the Germans in World War II.
Apart from the failures of the computer system, the cost of the project as a whole - including the training of the crew - also becomes a problem.
It is said to have reached the astronomical sum of 3.1 billion euros (3.6 billion dollars), up from 2.2 billion initially.
The problems of the new frigates are particularly important in the light of recent warnings that Germany's naval strength is declining.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament's defense committee, acknowledged earlier this year that the Navy is in fact  short of ships able to deploy .
The official said that the situation had a snowball effect over time, as the old ships were decommissioned but no replacement vessels were designated.
He regretted that none of the Baden-Württemberg-class frigates had been able to join the Navy.
The National Trust is monitoring the secret lives of bats
New research in a field in the Scottish Highlands is revealing how bats use the landscape in their search for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behavior of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
The study by researchers from the National Trust for Scotland will follow common bats and sopranos as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton bats at Winterweed Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also carry out mobile studies using portable detectors.
A professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of the bats' calls and the activities of the different species.
A map and habitat report will be drawn up to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour at the territorial level.
Rob Dewar, conservation adviser for the NTS, hopes the results will reveal the most important areas of habitat for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of grasslands and how best to preserve forests for bats and related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined considerably over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work which affects perch and leads to habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly-killing paper and certain chemical treatments of building materials, and attacks by pet cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to spot insects and obstacles in their flight path.
Responsible for protecting more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 acres of land across the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts who regularly conduct digging, inspections of the perch and occasionally rescue operations.
The organisation also established Scotland's first and only bat reserve at the Threave site in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's 10 bat species.
David Thompson, the estate manager, says that the site is the ideal territory for them.
"Here in Threave, we have a perfect place for bats", he said.
We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the good habitat.
But there is still much to learn about bats, so the work we are doing here and elsewhere will help us to better understand what bats need to thrive.
He stresses the importance of checking for bats before maintaining properties, as the unintentional destruction of a single mothering nest can result in the death of 400 females and young, or the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, disturb them, or destroy their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish director of the Bat Conservation Trust, urged the public to help.
She said:  We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species, we don't know what's going on in their populations yet. 
Ronaldo denies the rape charges as his lawyers prepare to sue a German magazine
Cristiano Ronaldo called the rape allegations against him "fake news" and said that people "want to be known" by using his name.
His lawyers are preparing to sue the German magazine Der Spiegel, which published the allegations.
The Portugal and Juventus striker was accused of raping an American woman named Kathryn Mayorga in a Las Vegas hotel room in 2009.
He then allegedly paid her $375,000 to keep quiet about the incident, Der Spiegel reported last Friday.
