No, no, no, no, and no.
What they said today is false information, the five-time Ballon d'Or winner told the camera.
They want to make a publicity using my name.
It's not unusual.
They want to be famous by saying my name, but it's part of the job.
I am a happy man and everything is fine , added the player with a smile.
According to Reuters, Ronaldo's lawyers are preparing to sue Der Spiegel over the allegations, which they have called "unacceptable denunciation of suspicion in the area of privacy".
Lawyer Christian Schertz said the player would seek compensation for the 'moral damage' in an amount proportionate to the seriousness of the offence, which is probably one of the most serious violations of human rights in recent years.
The alleged incident took place in June 2009 in a suite at the Palms Hotel and Casino in Las Vegas.
After meeting at a nightclub, Ronaldo and Mayorga apparently returned to the player's room, where an alleged anal rape occurred, according to court documents filed in Clark County, Nevada.
Mayorga claims that Ronaldo went down on his knees after the alleged incident and assured him that he was a "99% good guy" but that he didn't know what was going on with the remaining 1% of the population.
The documents claim that Ronaldo confirmed that the couple had had sexual relations, but that they had consented.
Mayorga also claimed that she went to the police and that photos of her injuries were taken in a hospital, but that she later accepted a settlement because she felt "terrified of retaliation" and feared "public humiliation".
