Ronaldo was about to join Real Madrid from Manchester United at the time of the alleged attack, and this summer, he joined Italian giant Juve in a €100 million deal.
Brexit: The UK would forever regret the departure of car manufacturers.
According to Greg Clark, the Secretary of State for Trade, the UK would "regret forever" if it lost its status as the world's leading car manufacturer after Brexit.
He added that it was "worrying" that Toyota UK had told the BBC that it would temporarily stop production at its Burnaston plant near Derby if Britain left the EU without an agreement.
"We need a deal", said Clark.
The Japanese carmaker indicated that the impact of border delays in the event of a no-deal Brexit could cost jobs.
The Burnaston plant - which makes Toyota's Auris and Avensis vehicles - built almost 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to other EU countries.
'I believe that if Britain leaves the EU at the end of March, production will stop at our plant,' said Marvin Cooke, Toyota's manager in Burnaston.
Other British carmakers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, have expressed their fear of leaving the EU without an agreement on how to operate cross-border trade.
For example, BMW says it will close its Mini plant in Oxford for a month following Brexit.
The biggest concerns are what carmakers say are risks to the supply chain in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line is run in a 'straight flow' with parts arriving every 37 minutes from suppliers in the UK and EU for the custom-built vehicles.
If the UK leaves the EU on 29 March without a deal, there could be disruption at the border, which the industry says could lead to delays and shortages of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to hold inventory for more than a day at its Derbyshire factory, the company said, and so production would be stopped.
According to Clark, Theresa May's Chequers plan for future relations with the EU is precisely calibrated to avoid these border checks.
"We need a deal, we want to have the best deal that will allow us, as I said, not only to enjoy the success of the moment, but also to seize this opportunity", he said on the BBC's Radio 4's Today programme.
 The evidence, not just from Toyota but from other manufacturers, is that we absolutely need to be able to maintain what has turned out to be a great set of supply chains. 
While Toyota was unable to say how long production would be halted, it did warn that in the longer term, the extra costs would reduce the competitiveness of the plant and eventually cost jobs.
Peter Tsouvallaris, the Unite union coordinator at the factory and who has worked at Burnaston for 24 years, said that his members were increasingly worried: "In my experience, once these jobs are gone, they never come back".
A government spokesman said:  We have proposed a clear and credible plan for our future relations with the EU. 
The White House says that the Trump-Rosenstein meeting may be delayed again.
The White House announced on Sunday that the high-stakes meeting between Donald Trump and Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein could be postponed for a week, while the fight for Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh continues.
Rosenstein oversees the work of Robert Mueller, the special counsel tasked with investigating Russian interference in the election, ties between Trump associates and Russia, and possible obstruction of justice by the president.
The question of whether or not Trump will fire the deputy attorney general, and thus jeopardize Mueller's independence, has been a hot topic in Washington for months.
Earlier this month, the New York Times reported that Rosenstein had talked about wearing a wire to record conversations with Trump and the possibility of eliminating the president by the 25th Amendment.
Rosenstein denied these claims.
However, last Monday, he showed up at the White House, as he was about to resign.
Instead, a meeting with Trump, who was then at the United Nations in New York, was announced for Thursday.
Trump indicated that he would prefer not to fire Mr. Rosenstein, but the meeting was postponed to avoid a clash with the Senate Judiciary Committee hearing in which Kavanaugh and Dr. Christine Blasey Ford, one of the women who accused him of sexual assault, testified.
On Friday, Trump directed the FBI to conduct a week-long investigation into the complaints against Kavanaugh, further delaying the Senate vote.
On Sunday, Trump press secretary Sarah Sanders made an appearance on Fox News.
Asked about the meeting with Rosenstein, she said:  No date has been set for that, it could be this week, I could see if they postpone it another week given all the other things going on at the Supreme Court.
But we'll see, and I'd like to keep the press informed.
This claim is disputed by some journalists: Since September 10, Sanders has not held any press conference at the White House.
Host Chris Wallace asked why.
Sanders responded that the rarity of the conferences was not due to an aversion to "demagogic" television reporters, although she did state: "I have nothing against them stunning the gallery".
Then she hinted that direct contact between Trump and the press would increase.
Without citing evidence, she added that  the president participates in more Q&A sessions than any president before him:  We checked the numbers. 
Press conferences will always be held, Sanders said, but if the press has the chance to directly question the president of the United States, it is infinitely better than talking to me.
We're trying to do it frequently, you've seen it in the last few weeks, and it's going to take the place of a press conference where you can talk to the president of the United States.
Trump regularly answers questions when he leaves the White House or when he attends public hearings or press conferences with dignitaries.
He rarely gives a press conference alone.
This week in New York, the president may have demonstrated why, by making a casual and at times bizarre appearance before the assembled press.
On Brexit fears, the Health Secretary writes to EU workers at NHS Scotland
The Secretary for Health has written to EU officials working in the Scottish NHS to express the country's gratitude and wishes for their continued employment after Brexit.
Scottish MP Jeane Freeman sent a letter less than six months before the UK is due to leave the EU.
