Foreign buyers will be subject to a higher stamp duty if they buy property in the UK
Foreign buyers will have to pay higher stamp duty if they buy property in the UK and the extra money will be used to help the homeless under the new Conservative schemes
This will undo the success of Corbyn's campaign to attract young voters.
The increase in stamp duty will be imposed on those who do not pay UK tax
The Treasury expects to collect up to £120 million a year to help the homeless.
Foreign buyers will be subject to a higher stamp duty rate if they buy property in the UK - the extra money will go to help the homeless, Theresa May announced today.
The move will be seen as an attempt to counter the success of Jeremy Corbyn's campaign to attract younger voters by pledging to provide more affordable housing and targeting high-income earners.
The increase in stamp duty will be levied on individuals and businesses who do not pay UK taxes, and the extra money will be used to bolster the government's efforts to help the homeless.
This surtax - which is added to the current stamp duty, including the higher levels introduced two years ago on second homes and buy-leases - could reach 3%.
The Treasury expects the project to raise up to £120 million a year.
Around 13% of new buildings in London are bought by non-UK residents, which drives up prices and prevents first-time buyers from gaining a foothold in the housing market.
Many wealthy areas of the country - especially in the capital - have become ghost towns because of the high number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the country.
This new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson demanded a reduction in stamp duty to help more young people buy their first homes.
Accusing large construction companies of keeping property prices high by squatting on land without using it, he called on Mrs May to give up quotas on affordable housing in order to tackle the UK's "housing shortage".
Mr Corbyn has put forward an attractive series of proposals for housing reform, including rent controls and the abolition of 'no-fault' evictions.
It also wants to give councils more powers to build new housing.
Mrs May said: Last year, I said I would dedicate my time as Prime Minister to the rebirth of the British dream - that every new generation would have a better life.
To do that, we need to fix our broken housing market.
Britain will always be open to anyone who wants to live, work and build a life here.
It is unfair, however, that it is as easy for non-UK residents and foreign companies to buy a house as it is for hardworking UK residents.
For far too many people, the dream of home ownership has become distant and the plight of the homeless remains too real. 
Jack Ross: My ultimate ambition is to lead Scotland.
Sunderland manager Jack Ross says his ultimate ambition is to become Scotland's head coach at some point.
The 42-year-old Scottishman is delighted with the challenge of re-establishing the North East club, which is currently in third place in League One, three points behind the leader.
He joined the Stadium of Light this summer after taking St Mirren to the Scottish Premier League last season.
I wanted to play for my country as a player.
I was selected for the B division and that's it", Ross told BBC Scotland's Sportsound.
But I grew up watching Scotland play in Hampden with my father and that's something I've never forgotten.
But that opportunity would only come if I succeeded in managing the club.
Ross's predecessors as Sunderland coaches include Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin ONeill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former coach of Alloa Athletic says he has no qualms about following such iconic names at such a big club, having already turned down offers from Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
 For me, the success of the moment will be measured in the light of the question  Can I bring this club back to the Premier League? 
The club's structure and infrastructure make it a Premier League club without a doubt, he added.
 It's not easy to get there, but I would probably consider myself a success here only if I could get the club back there. 
Ross has only three years of coaching experience, after a spell as an assistant at Dumbarton and 15 months on the Hearts coaching staff.
He then helped Alloa to rise from relegation to the third division and transformed St Mirren, who were on the verge of relegation, into the big winner of the championship the following season.
Ross said he was more comfortable now than he had been during his time at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
Taking charge of Alloa was probably a real crossroads, he recalls.
I really thought being a coach suited me better than playing.
It seems strange because I've been doing well, making a good living and enjoying some notable peaks.
But playing is sometimes difficult.
There are a lot of details to be worked out every week.
I continue to experience this in terms of stress and tension at work, but being a coach is fine with me.
I've always wanted to lead and now I'm doing it, I'm more comfortable in my own skin than I've ever been in my adult life.
