According to a survey, the ideal time for a pint is 5:30 on a Saturday.
The summer heat has boosted the revenues of struggling British pubs, but has added to the pressure on the restaurant chains.
The figures show that bar and pub groups recorded a 2.7 per cent increase in their sales in July, but revenues in restaurants fell by 4.8 per cent.
Peter Martin, of the CGA consultancy firm, which compiled the data, said: "The permanent sunshine and England's longer than expected World Cup participation meant that July followed the pattern of June, when bars had risen 2.8%, except for restaurants, which suffered an even bigger shock.
The decline of 1.8% in the catering sector in June worsened in July.
The pubs and bars where alcohol is served are by far the most popular, with more points of resemblance than restaurants.
Food stores have also been hit by the sun, but not as much as restaurant owners.
It seems like people just want to go out for a drink.
In pubs and bars, drink sales increased by 6.6% over the month and food sales decreased by 3%.
Paul Newman, RSM's leisure and hospitality analyst, said: "These results follow the trend seen since the end of April.
The weather and the impact of major social or sporting events remain the most important factors in sales in the off-market.
It is not surprising that catering groups continue to experience difficulties, although a decline in sales of 4.8% on average per year is particularly painful, in addition to ongoing cost pressures.
The long, hot summer could not have been less favourable for food business operators and time will tell whether the more moderate temperatures we experienced in August will provide a well-deserved respite. 
The total increase in sales in pubs and restaurants, including new openings, was 2.7% in July, reflecting the slowdown in employment.
Industry sales are monitored by the Coffer Peach Tracker for the UK pubs, bars and restaurants sector, which collects and analyses performance data from 47 operating groups, with a combined turnover of over £9 billion and is the established industry standard.
