Earthquakes and Tsunamis in Indonesia
At least 384 people were killed by a powerful earthquake and tsunami that devastated the Indonesian city of Palu on Friday, authorities said, and the death toll is expected to rise.
With communications paralyzed, rescue services could not receive any information from the Donggala Regency, an area north of Palu that is closer to the epicenter of the magnitude 7.5 earthquake.
In Palu, more than 16,000 people were evacuated as a result of the disaster.
Some key facts about Palu and Donggala on Sulawesi Island:
Palu is the capital of the Central Sulawesi province, located at the tip of a narrow bay on the west coast of Sulawesi Island, with an estimated population of 379,800 as of 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami hit.
Donggala is a regency that stretches over 300 km (180 miles) of coastline in the northwest of Sulawesi Island.
The population of the Regency, an administrative region below a province, was estimated at 299,200 in 2017.
Fishing and agriculture are the main pillars of the economy of Central Sulawesi province, and particularly of the coastal area of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also a major activity in the province, but is mainly located in Morowali on the opposite coast of Sulawesi.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunami several times in the last century, according to the Indonesian Disaster Mitigation Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
A tsunami also hit the west of Donggala in 1996, killing nine.
Indonesia is located on the Pacific seismic ring of fire and is regularly shaken by earthquakes.
Here are some of the major earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A major earthquake on December 26 off the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh triggered a tsunami that swept across 14 countries, killing 226,000 people along the Indian Ocean coastline, more than half of whom were in Aceh.
2005: Several strong earthquakes shook the west coast of Sumatra from late March to early April.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude earthquake struck southern Java, the most populated island in Indonesia, triggering a tsunami that struck the southern coast and killed nearly 700 people.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake shook the city of Padang, the capital of the province of West Sumatra.
Over 1,100 people were killed.
2010: A 7.5 magnitude earthquake devastated one of the Mentawai Islands off Sumatra, triggering a tsunami more than 10 meters (33 feet) deep that destroyed dozens of villages and killed about 300 people.
2016: A shallow earthquake rocked the Pidie Jaya regency in Aceh, causing destruction and panic, reminding residents of the devastation caused by the deadly 2004 earthquake and tsunami.
No tsunami was caused this time, but over 100 people were killed by collapsing buildings.
2018: Major earthquakes rocked the Indonesian tourist island of Lombok, killing more than 500 people, mostly on the north side of the island.
The earthquake destroyed several thousand buildings and left thousands of tourists temporarily stranded.
