Federal prosecutors are seeking a rare death sentence for a suspect in the New York City bombing.
Federal prosecutors in New York are seeking the death penalty for Sayfullo Saipov, the alleged New York City assailant who killed eight people - a rare sentence that hasn't been carried out in this state for a federal crime since 1953.
Saipov, 30, allegedly used a rented truck from Home Depot to attack a bike path on the West Side Highway in Lower Manhattan, killing pedestrians and a cyclist in October.
In order to justify a death sentence, prosecutors will have to provide evidence that Saipov  intentionally  murdered the eight victims and  intentionally  inflicted serious bodily harm, according to the statement of intent to seek the death penalty filed with the Southern District of New York.
Both charges are punishable by the death penalty, according to the court document.
A few weeks after the attack, a federal grand jury convicted Saipov of 22 counts, including eight counts of murder for extortion, usually used by federal prosecutors in organized crime cases, and one count of felony assault and destruction of motor vehicles.
The attack required careful preparation and premeditation, prosecutors said, calling the method used by Saipov "odious, cruel and depraved".
 Sayfullo Habibullaevic Saipov has caused injury, damage and loss to the families and friends of Diego Enrique Angelini, Nicholas Cleves, Ann-Laure Decadt, Darren Drake, Ariel Erlij, Hernan Ferruchi, Hernan Diego Mendoza and Alejandro Damian Pagnucco , the statement of intent states.
Five of the victims were Argentine tourists.
The Southern District of New York had not sought the death penalty in any of its ten-year-long lawsuits.
The defendant, Khalid Barnes, was found guilty of the murder of two drug traffickers but was subsequently sentenced to life imprisonment in September 2009.
The last time the death penalty was used in a New York federal case was in 1953 in the case of Julius and Ethel Rosenberg, a married couple executed for conspiracy and espionage for the USSR in the two years following the Cold War.
Both Rosenbergs were executed by electric chair on June 19, 1953.
